{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16371"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.14,0,0.77,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9062"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51656"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4875"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7202"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22149"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old woman is admitted to hospital for investigation of of a three month history of progressive difficulty speaking and swallowing. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cranial nerve examination reveals deviation of the protruded tongue to the left with visible atrophy and fasciculations of the left side of the tongue. MRI reveals a large tumour in the jugular foramen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves is most likely affected by these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glossopharyngeal nerve (IX)","Vagus nerve (X)","Accessory nerve (XI)","Hypoglossal nerve (XII)","Facial nerve (VII)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical findings of tongue deviation to the left with ipsilateral atrophy and fasciculations are characteristic of a left \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal nerve (XII)\u003C/strong\u003E lesion. The hypoglossal nerve innervates all intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue except palatoglossus. When damaged, the tongue deviates toward the affected side due to unopposed action of the contralateral genioglossus muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglossopharyngeal nerve (IX)\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the posterior third of the tongue and motor innervation to the stylopharyngeus muscle. Isolated lesions would not cause tongue deviation or atrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve (X)\u003C/strong\u003E provides parasympathetic innervation and innervates the muscles of the soft palate, pharynx, and larynx. Lesions typically cause dysphonia and dysphagia but not tongue deviation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccessory nerve (XI)\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles. Lesions cause weakness in head turning and shoulder elevation but do not affect tongue movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve (VII)\u003C/strong\u003E provides motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and taste sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue. It does not affect tongue movement or bulk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the tumour is located in the jugular foramen (through which cranial nerves IX, X, and XI pass), the hypoglossal nerve exits the skull through the hypoglossal canal. The tumour must be large enough to affect adjacent structures including the hypoglossal canal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cranial nerve XII (hypoglossal) innervates the intrinsic and extrinsic muscles of the tongue except palatoglossus.","Tongue deviation occurs towards the side of a hypoglossal nerve lesion due to unopposed action of the contralateral genioglossus muscle.","Jugular foramen syndrome can affect cranial nerves IX, X, and XI which exit through the foramen."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015).\u00a0Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","W\u0119giel A, Zielinska N, G\u0142owacka M, Olewnik \u0141. Hypoglossal Nerve Neuropathies-Analysis of Causes and Anatomical Background. Biomedicines. 2024 Apr 14;12(4):864. doi: 10.3390/biomedicines12040864. PMID: 38672218; PMCID: PMC11048189."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51656"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51656"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T14:54:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T14:55:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9062"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","